HEADWORD: Probatory
<hw>Pro"ba*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>probatoire</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Serving for trial;
probationary.</def> <rj><au>Abp. Bramhall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or serving for, proof.</def>
<rj><au>Jer. Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Probatory term</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a time for
taking testimony.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Probe</ent>⟦br⟧
